metadata.name: Boketto #22
metadata.description:
'Boketto' is the act of gazing vacantly into the distance without a thought.

On the process of making this collection, i explored interfering patterns in order to give an abstract and more painted look on the canvas.

--Features--

Palette : 14 different color palettes
Scheme : 11 different schemes
Step : 7 different steps
Rotation : 9 types (each type has more than 30 different outcomes)

Press "s" to save a 1600x2000 PNG

High resolution outputs will be uploaded on my (under contruction) site soon 

Made with p5js & ❤️

Gtsiliakos_art, October 2022

metadata.name: Mines #140
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: play/plaque #231
metadata.description:
A grid of trailing shapes. Each shape in the line wants to be like the shape in front of it.

The traits
4 shapes: square, cross, triangle, circle
5 grid sizes 1->5 with 1x1 grids being rarest (5%)
2 fill styles: hollow (80%, crosses can't be hollow) and filled (20%)
20% chance for all shapes to be the same
6 color palettes:
- Coffee and Blueberry
- Tropicana
- Monochrome
- Spectrum
- Peach and Pear
- Goji and Kelp

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao)

metadata.name: operation 01 #35
metadata.description:
A Voronoi field is the basis, inspired by Jonathan Reynold's "voronoi noise" sketch (available here: https://openprocessing.org/sketch/1015631 ). This starting point is used to create an abstract image that keeps drawing infinitely. Per-view randomization is introduced in the speed and size of the drawing of the arcs, to create the chaos, and in the placement of the Voronoi points. This ensures each viewing is unique. Three traits describe each individual mint:

Color: There are nine different color palettes, with "Bay" being a 20% likelihood, and all the others 10% likelihood.

Arc: This is the number of elements drawn around each point. There are three possible states, with 50 being a 10% likelihood, 5000 being a 20% likelihood, and 500 being the default at 70%. 

Resolution: This is the number of points in the Voronoi field. There are four candidates, with 1 being the least likely (10%), 2 and 10 having a 20% likelihood of occurring, and 5 being the most common at 50%. 

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Bifurcation Rains #123
metadata.description:
When you look at the cityscape outside the window through the glass with the raindrops, it always seems to be undecided about its choice of state and position in space. It flows and wriggles, becoming fluid, half-river, half-thought-out fantasy. 
Bifurcation diagrams are visually similar to these traces left by water on glass. We have tried to imagine a moving world, which right now is at a point of choice.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code
To save the image, press the 's' key. Enjoy!

October, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #976
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash
